ize=1> Eh? they're not that much different  Change the formula so that it displays the warrior getting the FBSS at 40 and never getting the RBG <p><center><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=8991"><img src="http://www.nadiar.com/pics/sig1.1.jpg"></a></center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/usiryakk.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Sir Yakk</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(4/10/02 11:12:58 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=641.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> ...</span><hr size=1> So, a few flaws:<br><br>Specialization effects.<br><br>Med tick missing chance based off casting time of spell (ie, on combat medding).  Looks like the chance is 50% in your table?  This is a factor of ManaburnPS, basically.<br><br>The &quot;minutes&quot; are in &quot;minutes per hour engaged&quot; right?  <br><br>Your item calculations are a bit wonkey.  You need a MPS (mana per second = Cost/CT) figure to work out exactly how much time one has to use the items.<br><br>Then<br>ItemTime = BattleTime - TotalMana/MPS<br>is a reasonably accurate measure of how much time is spent on item nuking.<br><br>(it fails in extreme cases, however -- as ItemTime gets close to 0, wierd effects occur if you don't use the Grim Aura trick.)<br><br>Lets assume that once you nuke, you don't sit down.  Then, you end up with a slightly different ManaburnPS (it is Mana/(CT + 2.5)).  The time you spend standing (in theory) in an hour is:<br><br>StandingTime(ticks) = ManaGainedInHour / MPTick<br><br>ManaGainedInHour = 600 * (ManaRegenEffects + 1) + (600 - StandingTime) * (MeddingRegen - 1)<br><br>(The + 1 is for idle regen, the -1 is to cancel out the + 1 that was already counted in the first half of the equation)<br><br><br>We care about ManaGainedInHour, so we have:<br><br>MGH = 600 * (MRE + 1) + (600 - MGH/MPT) (MR - 1)<br><br>MGH = 600 * MRE + 600 + 600 * MR - 600 - (MGH/MPT)*(MR -1)<br><br>MGH + (MGH/MPT)*(MR - 1) = 600 * (MRE + MR)<br><br>MGH * ((MR - 1)/MPT + 1) = 600 * (MRE + MR)<br>MGH = 600 * (MRE + MR) / ((MR-1)/MPT + 1)<br><br>Now, Ice Spear and Sundering have a MPT of 360 (I didn't sit down between them).<br><br>MR is 20.16, so we have . . .<br><br><br>600 * (26.5 + 20.16) / ((19.16)/360 + 1)<br><br>Or about 21050 mana per hour.<br><br>At a ratio around 3.9 &amp; 90% efficient, we get. . .<br><br>20.52 DPS over the hour, irrespective of the engagmement % really.<br><br>Now, let E be an efficiency increase, and Y be a MPT decrease.<br><br>27.0 * E / (19.16/(360*Y) + 1)<br><br>is your DPS.  Ie, with insta-casts (never missing a tick), you are doing 27.0 ish DPS.<br><br>Make Y be .1 (burn mana 10 times slower).  Let E be 1.5 (burn mana 50% faster).  No change in DPS.<br><br>Let Y be 1/6, and E be 2.  DPS only goes up by 1.5.<br><br>Toss in an item with a DPS of R.<br><br>ItemTime = (EnagementTime - NukeTime)<br>ItemDamage = ItemTime * R<br>ManaLostToItem = ItemTime * 19.16/6<br>DamageLostToItem = 11.18 * ItemTime<br><br>NetDamageCausedByItem = (R - 11.18) * (EngagmentTime-NukeTime)<br><br>Now, R is 47.04 for a Robe of Invocation.  So, we get a net swing of 35.86 DPS for every second you use it.  =)  Well, not quite, not that easy.<br><br>See, less medding = less MPH = less nuke time = more item time = less medding.  =)<br><br>Luckily, MPH is much easier to calculate if you are chain-using an item.  It is simply<br><br>MGH = 600 * (37 + 20.16 - EngagementPercent * 19.16)<br>= 28.2 k - 11.5 k * EngagementTime/3600<br><br>NukeTime = MGH/MPS = MGH / (60*Y)<br>= 60 * (7.8 - 3.2 * ET / 3600) / Y<br><br>And, NukingDPS under this model is:<br>NDPS = E * MGH / 1000<br>or so.  And<br>IDPS = ItemDamage / 3600<br><br>Thus, total DPS is:<br>DPS = IDPS + NDPS<br>= (35.86 * (ET - NT))/3600 + MGH / 1000<br>~= <br>(ET - 60 * (7.8 - 3.2 * ET / 3600) / Y) / 100) &gt;&gt; IDPS +<br>E * (28.2 - 11.5 * ET/3600)<br>~=<br>((ET - ET/(20*Y) )/100 - 4.68) &gt;&gt; IDPS +<br>28.2 * E - 11.5 * E * ET/3600<br>~=<br>ET/100 - ET/2000Y - 4.68 + 28.2 * E - E * ET / 327<br>~= (assume Y = E = 1)<br>ET/80 + 23.5<br><br>So, for a 20 minute battle, we have a spell+item DPS of:<br>38.5 DPS<br>40 minites per hour:<br>53.5 DPS<br><br>Which matches them with rogues in 33% (20 minute) hours, and warriors in 66% (40 minute) hours.<br><br>Whew.  Feel like using some of the blather above to improve the spreadsheet?<br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/uarmok.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Armok</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Sorcerer<br>Need a log parsed?</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(4/12/02 10:34:19 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=641.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ...</span><hr size=1> Sir Yakk,<br><br>You put a lot of work into analyzing the forumlas involved. Thanks for all the effort: it helps to improve the estimation. I'll address the issues you raise, but skimp a bit on the forumlas to keep it readable. For more information on the derivation of my forumlas, visit the following thread: <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm10.showMessage?topicID=603.topic">pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffe...=603.topic</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br><br>On to your comments:<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Specialization effects.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>Yeah, I negelected to account for these. When I originally derived the formula, AA skills weren't in yet, and the exact effect of specialization was not known (by me, at least). We now have a better understanding of both, and future versions will account for it. Interestingly enough, the numbers worked out close enough when I discounted specialization altogether (meaning predicted results were close to measured results).<br><!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Med tick missing chance based off casting time of spell (ie, on combat medding). Looks like the chance is 50% in your table?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Yes. This is a heuristic and is lower than you would expect because of sit agro. I found I was unable to med in combat as much as I liked because sit agro would prevent it. I discounted meditation in combat entirely when item nuking because I found that when I was item nuking I was never meditating in combat, ever. I was either clicking or casting or standing to avoid sit agro.<br><!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> The &quot;minutes&quot; are in &quot;minutes per hour engaged&quot; right?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Yes.<br><!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Your item calculations are a bit wonkey.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Yes, this is a bit convoluted. Basically, using straightline theoretical numbers always came out significantly higher than my measured numbers. I struggled with a few approaches to make everything balance out and hit on the right factor when I accounted for average fight time and item cast time. The above thread covers this in more detail, but think about the PoG robe for a minute. It has a cast time of 28 seconds. Lets say that your average fight time is 30 seconds. Some fights will be more, some less. If you are only item nuking, and click your robe as soon as the pull arrives at the camp, your nuke will land on a corpse an average of every other fight (some fights will take less than 30 seconds, remember). If you are responsible for snare, then the mob will likely be in runaway mode before your nuke lands, so it will move out of range before the nuke goes off every single time (not to mention that you'd find yourself fired from snare duty if you kept that up). The formula I concocted is based on (1/(1+x)) and gives the shape I liked, approaching zero when combat time = click time, but approaching full right click efficiency when combat time approaches infinity. The actual formula is as follows:<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> ACT = Average Combat Time (per opponent, in seconds)<br>IAT = Item Activation Time (in seconds: raw number + 1)<br>IDPS = Item's effective DPS<br>SE = Item's Spell Efficiency. I use 100% for lure, 95% for magic, and 90% for fire/cold.<br>X = Item use factor (roughly, how many times in a combat the item could theorhetically be used).<br><br>Here are the formulas:<br>X = ACT / IAT<br>rawdps = (item dmg) / IAT<br>IDPS = SE * rawdps * (1 - (2/(X + 1)))<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>Applying this forumla to my Rend Robe sessions predicted damage within about 5%. Straight line formulas (such as yours) usually overestimated damage from items by 30-50%.<br><br>I should note that I completely discounted cast time of wizard nukes because I found that agro prevented me from nuking/medding efficiently enough for it to become a factor.<br><br>Anyway, thanks again for taking the time to carefully examine my formulas and provide some insightful commentary. I will account for specialization (and Spec Mastery) in my next version, but there's no ETA on this being done. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/usiryakk.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Sir Yakk</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(4/12/02 5:55:30 pm